WEBVTT

00:01.120 --> 00:03.540
Dre: For the month of February,

00:03.540 --> 00:05.170
America celebrates
Black History Month

00:05.170 --> 00:09.250
with low interest rates
and no overdraft fees.

00:09.250 --> 00:13.000
Companies run ads
dedicated to us.

00:13.000 --> 00:14.540
It's great while it lasts,

00:14.540 --> 00:17.460
but come the end of February,
it is over.

00:17.460 --> 00:18.710
How was school?

00:18.710 --> 00:21.380
A squirrel got into the gym,
so I'd say pretty good.

00:21.380 --> 00:22.500
Mm.

00:22.500 --> 00:24.750
Baby girl.
What are you doing?

00:24.750 --> 00:27.170
Oh, well, Black History Month
is pretty much over,

00:27.170 --> 00:29.040
so Ms. Davis sent
all our projects home.

00:29.040 --> 00:31.500
See you next year,
Harriet.

00:31.500 --> 00:33.420
What the hell?!

00:36.420 --> 00:38.420
♪♪

00:38.420 --> 00:39.580
Hey!

00:39.580 --> 00:43.620
You cannot toss Harriet Tubman
in the trash!

00:43.620 --> 00:45.330
Why not?

00:45.330 --> 00:46.920
Damn it, Jack!
What are you doing?!

00:46.920 --> 00:49.000
Dad -- Dad, it's fine!

00:49.000 --> 00:51.080
It's not Harriet Tubman.
It's Frederick Douglass.

00:51.080 --> 00:52.710
I believe what your dad is
trying to say

00:52.710 --> 00:54.790
is that you shouldn't be
throwing these away at all.

00:54.790 --> 00:56.620
Ohhh! I get it.

00:56.620 --> 00:58.210
So -- So we can
use them next year

00:58.210 --> 01:00.210
when we do
the same reports again.

01:00.210 --> 01:01.750
That's why
you're the dad.

01:01.750 --> 01:03.540
What do you mean,
the same reports?

01:03.540 --> 01:04.830
Does everyone just do

01:04.830 --> 01:07.000
Frederick Douglass
and Harriet Tubman every year?

01:07.000 --> 01:08.960
Yeah.
Well, mostly everyone.

01:08.960 --> 01:11.460
Joshua Miller was supposed to do
George Washington Carver,

01:11.460 --> 01:13.170
but he has
a horrible peanut allergy,

01:13.170 --> 01:14.420
so he switched back
to Harriet.

01:15.670 --> 01:18.170
Mnh-mnh, mnh-mnh,
mnh-mnh-mnh.

01:18.170 --> 01:19.170
Can you believe this?

01:19.170 --> 01:20.460
No, I can't.

01:20.460 --> 01:23.080
Joshua Miller -- he gets
so much special treatment.

01:23.080 --> 01:24.290
Drives me nuts.

01:24.290 --> 01:26.960
No! I mean, this is
the same sort of crap

01:26.960 --> 01:28.620
they did
when I went to school.

01:28.620 --> 01:30.420
The reason I went
to Howard University

01:30.420 --> 01:32.420
was to get the full picture
of Black history.

01:32.420 --> 01:34.210
I get it.

01:34.210 --> 01:36.000
You know, I hoped that 30 years
would've made a difference,

01:36.000 --> 01:37.580
but, babe,
our children are getting

01:37.580 --> 01:39.290
the same
surface education.

01:39.290 --> 01:40.960
I know. I know.

01:40.960 --> 01:43.330
It is...frustrating.

01:43.330 --> 01:46.330
But, Dre, I mean...
[ Sighs ]

01:46.330 --> 01:48.000
...Black History Month
is almost over.

01:48.000 --> 01:49.580
There's only two more days.
What are you gonna do?
[ Sighs ]

01:49.580 --> 01:51.670
You gonna go down there
and make a scene?

01:51.670 --> 01:54.040
♪♪

01:54.040 --> 01:55.670
[ Door bangs ]
Aah! [ Gasps ]

01:55.670 --> 01:56.710
Davis!

01:56.710 --> 01:58.620
Mr. Johnson.

01:58.620 --> 02:01.540
You are supposed to email me
before you come in.

02:01.540 --> 02:02.790
We had a deal.

02:02.790 --> 02:04.290
Yeah, and I thought
we had a deal --

02:04.290 --> 02:07.500
I pay you,
you educate my children.

02:07.500 --> 02:10.380
But after hearing about
your Black History Month lesson,

02:10.380 --> 02:12.000
you owe me
a lot of change.

02:12.000 --> 02:14.250
I tried so hard
this year.

02:14.250 --> 02:16.790
We studied Harriet Tubman,
Dr. King,

02:16.790 --> 02:20.000
Frederick Douglass,
and George Washington Carver.

02:20.000 --> 02:21.540
But you didn't
have to stop there.

02:21.540 --> 02:23.170
All right, there are
a million people

02:23.170 --> 02:24.580
that you could have
kept talking about.

02:24.580 --> 02:26.420
Hell, if you had just picked
one person

02:26.420 --> 02:27.920
that Chadwick Boseman
played,

02:27.920 --> 02:30.750
I would not be yelling at you,
despite our agreement --

02:30.750 --> 02:32.620
which I never signed,
by the way.

02:32.620 --> 02:34.380
Well, tomorrow is

02:34.380 --> 02:37.210
our "Farewell to
Black History Month" assembly.

02:37.210 --> 02:40.670
Now, I was going to show
the PG parts of "Get Out,"

02:40.670 --> 02:43.920
but, hey, since you know so much
about this stuff,

02:43.920 --> 02:47.290
maybe you could come in
and teach the students

02:47.290 --> 02:50.080
about one more Black person
they should know.

02:50.080 --> 02:52.710
Ohhh, would you like me
to do that for you?

02:52.710 --> 02:54.790
[ Exhales sharply ]
I'd be so relieved

02:54.790 --> 02:56.330
if you took it
off my plate.

02:56.330 --> 02:57.460
No!

02:57.460 --> 02:58.920
Do your job, Davis!

02:58.920 --> 03:00.290
Mr. Johnson.

03:00.290 --> 03:01.920
You're supposed to email
before you come.

03:01.920 --> 03:03.540
We had a deal.

03:03.540 --> 03:05.120
Which I never signed.

03:05.120 --> 03:07.040
But I was
just leaving.

03:09.210 --> 03:11.960
W-- Maybe you could
point me in the direction

03:11.960 --> 03:14.080
of a good Black person?

03:14.080 --> 03:16.040
Okay, let's unpack
what you just said.

03:16.040 --> 03:17.040
What?

03:17.040 --> 03:18.670
You did a racism.

03:18.670 --> 03:19.920
Again?

03:19.920 --> 03:22.500
[ Exhales sharply ]

03:22.500 --> 03:24.420
Uh-oh.

03:24.420 --> 03:26.170
[ Sighs heavily ]
Okay, Dre, what's wrong?

03:26.170 --> 03:28.540
My kids' teacher
asked me to choose

03:28.540 --> 03:31.330
a new person to talk about
for Black History Month.

03:31.330 --> 03:35.120
Once again, the Black man
has to educate White people.

03:35.120 --> 03:37.040
[ Scoffs ]
Tell me about it.

03:37.040 --> 03:38.250
Most of them
don't even know

03:38.250 --> 03:41.210
that Harriet Tubman
invented the tub.

03:41.210 --> 03:43.210
That's why
most Home Depot employees

03:43.210 --> 03:45.380
look so confused when you ask
to see the Harriets.

03:45.380 --> 03:46.420
Know what
I'm talking about?

03:46.420 --> 03:47.710
You know
what I'm talking about, right?

03:47.710 --> 03:48.710
No.
No.

03:48.710 --> 03:49.790
No, I don't.
No.

03:49.790 --> 03:51.210
You know what?

03:51.210 --> 03:53.920
So, I told her,
"No. It's your job, not mine."

03:53.920 --> 03:55.380
Good choice, Dre.

03:55.380 --> 03:57.170
Besides, the only thing
you need to know

03:57.170 --> 03:59.620
about Black History Month
are the top four, right?

03:59.620 --> 04:01.960
Tubman, Carver,
King, Sinbad.

04:01.960 --> 04:03.250
Sinbad's
not on that list.

04:03.250 --> 04:04.750
Well,
he should be, okay?

04:04.750 --> 04:06.540
'Cause he would
lighten it up. Huh?

04:06.540 --> 04:09.040
You ever heard his routine
about riding the bus?

04:09.040 --> 04:10.710
[ Laughing ]
It's hysterical.

04:10.710 --> 04:12.040
Mr. Stevens has a point.

04:12.040 --> 04:13.880
Black History Month
is kind of a bummer.

04:13.880 --> 04:15.290
It's all slavery

04:15.290 --> 04:17.250
and people getting blasted
by fire hoses.

04:17.250 --> 04:20.250
Which is actually why
we gave you the shortest month.

04:20.250 --> 04:22.920
Nobody "gave" us
the shortest month.

04:22.920 --> 04:27.330
In the 1920s, a Black historian
by the name of Carter G. Woodson

04:27.330 --> 04:29.880
chose February
because it coincided

04:29.880 --> 04:33.500
with Abraham Lincoln and
Frederick Douglass' birthday.

04:33.500 --> 04:35.790
The original focus
of Black History Month

04:35.790 --> 04:39.460
was not slavery
or civil rights, all right?

04:39.460 --> 04:42.920
It was created to illustrate our
contribution to American life

04:42.920 --> 04:44.920
and celebrate
Black excellence.

04:44.920 --> 04:46.790
Well, hearing that
actually kind of makes me want

04:46.790 --> 04:47.960
to know more
about Black history.

04:47.960 --> 04:49.290
Like double-dutch.

04:49.290 --> 04:51.000
What is the deal
with that?

04:51.000 --> 04:53.790
Counterpoint --
most people don't want to learn

04:53.790 --> 04:55.790
more than they have to,
right?

04:55.790 --> 04:57.000
I mean,
let's be honest.

04:57.000 --> 04:58.580
You're lucky
I know about the top four.

04:58.580 --> 05:00.880
And, yes, I'm keeping
Sinbad in there.

05:00.880 --> 05:02.120
He's a genius.

05:02.120 --> 05:03.670
I just seen him
recently, too.

05:03.670 --> 05:05.620
Sinbad?
At the dollar store.

05:05.620 --> 05:07.000
Ballin'.

05:07.000 --> 05:09.670
Listening to all the ignorance
in the room,

05:09.670 --> 05:13.790
I realized it was my job
to educate that school.

05:13.790 --> 05:16.210
No one else was going to
dig below the surface

05:16.210 --> 05:18.080
to bring Black history to life.

05:18.080 --> 05:19.420
No more
candy machines.

05:19.420 --> 05:20.830
Finally, you're back.

05:20.830 --> 05:22.750
Hey, Junior, Mom,
come on in here!

05:22.750 --> 05:24.000
Gather 'round!

05:24.000 --> 05:26.710
I got something that is going to
blow your minds!

05:26.710 --> 05:28.170
Oh, my God.

05:28.170 --> 05:29.670
Yep, come on.

05:29.670 --> 05:32.500
I've been poring over books
and the Internet all day,

05:32.500 --> 05:34.290
and I have come up with
the perfect person

05:34.290 --> 05:36.420
to present to Valley Glen
tomorrow.

05:36.420 --> 05:37.750
It's going to be --

05:37.750 --> 05:38.920
Drumroll, please.

05:40.750 --> 05:41.750
Ah!

05:41.750 --> 05:44.420
...Lewis Latimer!

05:44.420 --> 05:46.620
Isn't he a free safety
for the Eagles?

05:46.620 --> 05:47.790
No!

05:47.790 --> 05:49.170
Okay, you know what?

05:49.170 --> 05:53.040
I'm gonna tell you all about
Lewis Howard Latimer.

05:53.040 --> 05:56.920
Lewis Howard Latimer
was born in 1848,

05:56.920 --> 05:59.120
the child of runaway slaves.

05:59.120 --> 06:01.500
He earned multiple patents,

06:01.500 --> 06:04.250
including one
for the carbon filament

06:04.250 --> 06:07.250
which paved the way
for our modern lightbulb.

06:08.460 --> 06:10.620
And that's a Black person
you should know.

06:10.620 --> 06:13.830
[ Gospel organ music plays ]

06:13.830 --> 06:15.500
Wait a minute. So...

06:15.500 --> 06:17.790
you're coming in
with a lightbulb guy

06:17.790 --> 06:19.960
who died
a hundred years ago?

06:19.960 --> 06:20.960
Pass.

06:20.960 --> 06:22.040
But he's an inspiration.

06:22.040 --> 06:23.290
To who?

06:23.290 --> 06:24.920
Okay, okay, okay, guys.
"To who"?!

06:24.920 --> 06:27.670
Your dad obviously worked
very hard on this,

06:27.670 --> 06:29.210
and he's excited.

06:29.210 --> 06:30.210
Thank you, Bow.
Mm-hmm.

06:30.210 --> 06:32.080
Look, I researched this
all day,

06:32.080 --> 06:33.460
and I am confident
that I have --

06:33.460 --> 06:36.540
But I think that if we all
put our heads together,

06:36.540 --> 06:38.750
we could come up
with someone amazing.

06:38.750 --> 06:39.880
Mae Jemison!

06:39.880 --> 06:41.670
W.E.B. Du Bois.

06:41.670 --> 06:42.670
Aretha!

06:42.670 --> 06:43.880
Ahh, Ta-Nehisi Coates.

06:43.880 --> 06:45.500
Chance the Rapper!
Beyoncé.

06:45.500 --> 06:46.500
Jackie Robinson.
Spike Lee.

06:46.500 --> 06:47.880
Alvin Ailey.
Mahalia Jackson.

06:47.880 --> 06:49.580
Serena and Venus.
Black Panther!

06:49.580 --> 06:51.500
But I've already
picked my guy!

06:55.540 --> 06:57.460
You know who would be
really good?
Who?

06:57.460 --> 06:58.620
James Baldwin.

06:58.620 --> 07:00.080
That's really good.
Yeah!

07:00.080 --> 07:01.830
Or -- Or Jay-Z
or Kendrick Lamar --

07:01.830 --> 07:02.790
Okay, okay, no!

07:02.790 --> 07:04.250
Stop naming names!

07:04.250 --> 07:05.420
You know what?

07:05.420 --> 07:07.880
I am calling
a family meeting!

07:07.880 --> 07:10.580
Um...we are all here
already.

07:10.580 --> 07:13.500
But no one
is listening to me.

07:13.500 --> 07:15.920
I have one shot tomorrow
to prove to that school

07:15.920 --> 07:17.920
that we are more
than those stock images

07:17.920 --> 07:19.580
that they see once a year,

07:19.580 --> 07:24.380
by introducing them
to an unsung Black hero --

07:24.380 --> 07:27.040
Lewis Howard Latimer!

07:27.040 --> 07:30.040
Why can't you take a look at
people who are making an impact

07:30.040 --> 07:32.750
on Black life and culture
right now?

07:32.750 --> 07:35.750
Yes. Ooh. I have someone
super exciting to pitch you.

07:35.750 --> 07:36.670
Don't say "LeBron."

07:37.880 --> 07:38.790
Okay. [ Scoffs ]

07:39.750 --> 07:41.920
It's LeBron.

07:41.920 --> 07:46.790
LeBron James is the greatest
basketball player of all time,

07:46.790 --> 07:49.830
with three NBA titles,
four MVPs,

07:49.830 --> 07:51.750
and fourteen trips
to the All-Star game.

07:51.750 --> 07:53.960
He's even more amazing
off the court --

07:53.960 --> 07:56.710
raising money for charity,
standing up to bigots,

07:56.710 --> 07:59.620
and opening a public school
for struggling kids.

07:59.620 --> 08:02.500
And that's a Black person
you should know.

08:02.500 --> 08:07.040
Seriously, he's good people.

08:07.040 --> 08:08.040
[ Gospel organ music plays ]

08:08.040 --> 08:09.790
I mean,
your guy Latimer's okay,

08:09.790 --> 08:12.540
but he was never down 3-1
to the Warriors.

08:12.540 --> 08:14.040
Down 3-1?!

08:14.040 --> 08:18.460
Son, Latimer fought
in the Civil War!

08:18.460 --> 08:20.880
The South was easier to beat
than the Warriors.

08:20.880 --> 08:22.330
Look, LeBron is LeBron,

08:22.330 --> 08:25.420
but Black History Month is about
teaching the classics

08:25.420 --> 08:27.750
so that White people
can eat peanut butter

08:27.750 --> 08:29.210
and say,
"Thank you, Black man."

08:29.210 --> 08:31.460
[ Laughs ]
"Thank you, Black man."

08:31.460 --> 08:33.710
I actually have
a suggestion.
What is it?

08:33.710 --> 08:35.670
Don't embarrass us
in front of our whole school!

08:35.670 --> 08:36.880
Embarrass you how?

08:36.880 --> 08:38.420
Come on!

08:38.420 --> 08:40.290
Diane!

08:40.290 --> 08:43.960
We get to shine the light
on Black political pioneers.

08:43.960 --> 08:46.120
[ Gasps ]
Like Shirley Chisholm.

08:46.120 --> 08:50.040
Or Black sexiness pioneers,
like Denzel Washington.

08:50.040 --> 08:51.250
Oh, my God.
[ Laughter ]

08:51.250 --> 08:52.380
[ Laughs loudly ]

08:52.380 --> 08:55.000
No, Mama,
I've done my research.

08:55.000 --> 08:56.580
"Research."
Yes.

08:56.580 --> 09:01.330
So you've researched
400 years of Black excellence,

09:01.330 --> 09:02.830
and you came up
with a man?

09:02.830 --> 09:03.960
[ Gasps ]
That's shocking.

09:03.960 --> 09:04.960
Mm.
Mm-hmm.

09:04.960 --> 09:06.000
Did you look
at DeRay Mckesson?

09:06.000 --> 09:07.670
[ Scoffs ]

09:07.670 --> 09:11.330
Of course...I looked at...
DeR-- DeRay Mckesson.

09:11.330 --> 09:13.250
DeRay Mckesson.

09:15.790 --> 09:18.420
DeRay Mckesson...

09:18.420 --> 09:20.080
And that's a Black person
you should know?

09:20.080 --> 09:22.210
[ Gospel organ music plays ]

09:24.380 --> 09:25.580
[ Groans ]
Oh, God.

09:25.580 --> 09:26.580
Oh, my God.
What's wrong, baby?

09:26.580 --> 09:27.790
Ain't nothing wrong
with him.

09:27.790 --> 09:28.920
Ooh, I got the bubble guts
out of nowhere.

09:28.920 --> 09:29.920
You didn't even
eat today!

09:29.920 --> 09:31.290
Yes, I did!
[ Groaning ]

09:31.290 --> 09:32.290
Dre...

09:32.290 --> 09:33.380
[ Indistinct talking ]

09:33.380 --> 09:34.420
[ Chuckles ]

09:34.420 --> 09:36.830
I got you now, DeRay.

09:39.750 --> 09:41.040
[ Thud ]
I --

09:42.460 --> 09:43.920
Are you watching TV?

09:43.920 --> 09:45.170
[ Chuckling ]
Uh, no, no, baby.

09:45.170 --> 09:46.170
That was just my stomach.

09:47.710 --> 09:49.750
Uhh...
a-a little mystery, Bow!

09:49.750 --> 09:51.000
Dre, you're --

09:51.000 --> 09:52.040
[ Groans ]
Open the door.

09:52.040 --> 09:54.790
Open -- Open --
Open the door, please!

09:54.790 --> 09:56.500
Seriously, Dre?

09:56.500 --> 10:00.580
Did you come up here
to look up DeRay Mckesson?

10:00.580 --> 10:02.080
You can't even tell Junior

10:02.080 --> 10:03.420
he came up with someone
you didn't know?

10:03.420 --> 10:05.920
No, I cannot.

10:05.920 --> 10:07.880
I hate it when the kids
know more than I do.

10:07.880 --> 10:10.170
So you go downstairs
and you tell your son

10:10.170 --> 10:12.710
that he needs to be more
respectful to his patriarch!

10:12.710 --> 10:14.830
I will do no such thing!

10:14.830 --> 10:16.290
You should listen.

10:16.290 --> 10:17.620
Maybe you'll learn
something.

10:19.500 --> 10:21.290
Do you even know me?

10:21.290 --> 10:22.670
You know what?
You're right, Dre.

10:22.670 --> 10:25.710
It's definitely more productive
for you to sit on a toilet

10:25.710 --> 10:28.420
and watch videos
of DeRay Mckesson

10:28.420 --> 10:31.210
so that you can win an argument
with a child.

10:32.830 --> 10:34.210
Thank you.
Mm.

10:34.210 --> 10:36.080
While you're at it,
why don't you look up

10:36.080 --> 10:38.880
Patrisse Cullors, Opal Tometi,
and Alicia Garza.

10:38.880 --> 10:40.500
Couple women, huh?

10:40.500 --> 10:41.790
Three of 'em.
Mm-hmm.

10:41.790 --> 10:44.380
My, uh...

10:44.380 --> 10:46.080
My hands are kind of full
right now, Bow.

10:46.080 --> 10:48.210
Happy Black History Month.
Yeah.

10:48.210 --> 10:50.250
[ Clicks tongue ]
Power to the people.

10:50.250 --> 10:52.120
Hey.
Hey.

10:52.120 --> 10:53.580
How crazy is it

10:53.580 --> 10:56.380
that every person
they came up with is a man?

10:56.380 --> 10:57.380
Okay?

10:57.380 --> 10:58.960
Psht.
Are you surprised?

10:58.960 --> 11:01.330
No, look, I think they were all
really good suggestions,

11:01.330 --> 11:03.420
but we all know

11:03.420 --> 11:08.620
that the real unsung heroes
of Black history are women.

11:08.620 --> 11:09.710
Got that right!

11:09.710 --> 11:11.790
Like Joycelyn Elders.

11:11.790 --> 11:16.580
Joycelyn Elders became the first
Black Surgeon General in 1993.

11:16.580 --> 11:19.040
She used her position
to talk about

11:19.040 --> 11:21.040
sex education and drug addiction

11:21.040 --> 11:23.380
in a way
that cut through sound bites

11:23.380 --> 11:25.750
and addressed
people's real lives.

11:25.750 --> 11:27.290
Okay, now.

11:27.290 --> 11:29.880
And that's a Black person
you should know.

11:29.880 --> 11:33.250
[ Gospel organ music plays ]

11:33.250 --> 11:34.710
I thought you said
"unsung."

11:34.710 --> 11:35.960
Mm-hmm.

11:35.960 --> 11:37.290
Like me!
Oh, my God.

11:37.290 --> 11:41.080
Rubilene Johnson,
mother of Black America!

11:41.080 --> 11:41.830
Okay.
[ Chuckles ]

11:41.830 --> 11:44.500
Ruby, last week,

11:44.500 --> 11:47.040
you wouldn't even let me
use your Costco card.

11:47.040 --> 11:49.080
The mother of Black America

11:49.080 --> 11:51.420
doesn't participate
in fraud, Rainbow.

11:51.420 --> 11:52.540
[ Both laugh ]
Okay.

11:52.540 --> 11:53.920
That's right.

11:53.920 --> 11:54.920
Diane.
Mm-hmm?

11:54.920 --> 11:57.960
Who is your Black she-ro?

11:57.960 --> 11:59.880
It's actually Miss Biggs.

11:59.880 --> 12:02.960
Shirlette Biggs is
the first Black principal

12:02.960 --> 12:04.250
of Valley Glen Prep.

12:04.250 --> 12:06.790
When she talks, people listen.

12:06.790 --> 12:10.290
And she has a contraband drawer
that's the stuff of legend.

12:10.290 --> 12:12.920
We're talking fireworks,
explicit mixtapes,

12:12.920 --> 12:15.460
even a shiv.

12:15.460 --> 12:18.120
And that's a Black person
you should know.

12:19.210 --> 12:20.880
Shivs at school.

12:20.880 --> 12:22.040
Damn.

12:22.040 --> 12:25.290
[ Gospel organ music plays ]

12:25.290 --> 12:26.880
Aww, Diane.

12:26.880 --> 12:30.120
That's cute, but no.

12:30.120 --> 12:34.210
Oprah Winfrey is the first
Black female billionaire.

12:34.210 --> 12:35.250
Oh, yeah.

12:35.250 --> 12:37.170
But go ahead,
pick your principal.

12:37.170 --> 12:38.290
[ Both laugh ]

12:38.290 --> 12:39.460
Okay.

12:39.460 --> 12:41.620
Just forget
I said anything.

12:41.620 --> 12:43.080
What?
[ Devante crying ]

12:43.080 --> 12:45.000
Diane.
Oh. That's Devante.

12:45.000 --> 12:46.120
I'm gonna go
check on him.

12:46.120 --> 12:47.620
I'm coming, baby.

12:47.620 --> 12:49.460
Ha-ha!

12:49.460 --> 12:52.290
So, you don't think
I know anything

12:52.290 --> 12:56.000
about DeRay...Mckesson?

12:56.000 --> 12:58.210
DeRay Mckesson.

12:58.210 --> 13:00.210
He's a young activist
on the front lines

13:00.210 --> 13:02.670
of the current fight
for civil rights,

13:02.670 --> 13:05.750
advocating for fairer policing
practices on the streets

13:05.750 --> 13:08.830
and fairer sentencing practices
in America's courts.

13:10.040 --> 13:12.580
And that's a Black person
you should know.

13:12.580 --> 13:13.580
Boom.

13:13.580 --> 13:16.710
[ Gospel organ music plays ]

13:16.710 --> 13:18.290
What do you say?

13:18.290 --> 13:19.960
I mean, I feel like
he could be pretty inspiring

13:19.960 --> 13:21.420
for the kids at school.

13:21.420 --> 13:23.330
Eh, he's interesting.
I give you that.

13:23.330 --> 13:26.420
But his history
has not been written yet.

13:26.420 --> 13:28.420
All right, let's give him
his due when he's accomplished

13:28.420 --> 13:30.330
everything that
he's going to accomplish.

13:30.330 --> 13:32.380
That's exactly
what I've been saying.

13:32.380 --> 13:33.750
You know
who's accomplished a lot?

13:33.750 --> 13:34.790
Harriet Tubman.

13:34.790 --> 13:36.250
Harriet Tubm--

13:36.250 --> 13:38.380
Stop it! All right?
Everybody knows about her.

13:38.380 --> 13:40.580
You're not bringing anything
to this conversation.

13:40.580 --> 13:42.120
I'm sorry.
What was that?

13:42.120 --> 13:44.080
He said you're not bringing
anything to the conversation.

13:45.250 --> 13:46.830
Oh, I am
so through with this.

13:46.830 --> 13:48.080
Huh.

13:48.080 --> 13:50.920
You know,
we were in the kitchen

13:50.920 --> 13:53.750
talking about
some amazing women

13:53.750 --> 13:54.830
you should be
thinking about.

13:54.830 --> 13:56.250
No, you were.

13:56.250 --> 13:58.500
Okay, look, I will admit

13:58.500 --> 14:01.380
not all of your suggestions
were terrible,

14:01.380 --> 14:04.380
but I can only choose
one person to present tomorrow,

14:04.380 --> 14:06.290
and that person
is Latimer.

14:06.290 --> 14:08.380
I'm the one with the degree
in this stuff.

14:08.380 --> 14:09.790
I think I know
what I'm talking about.

14:09.790 --> 14:11.210
Do you?

14:11.210 --> 14:12.170
'Cause I'm pretty sure
you just looked up

14:12.170 --> 14:13.920
DeRay Mckesson
in the bathroom.

14:13.920 --> 14:15.960
You lie.

14:15.960 --> 14:18.290
See, we're all
just wasting our breath.

14:18.290 --> 14:20.250
Dre's the one
with the fancy degree.

14:20.250 --> 14:24.540
Been telling us for 20 years
that he's Mr. Black History.

14:24.540 --> 14:27.040
You can't even get on
the Black History Month poster

14:27.040 --> 14:28.380
until he approves.

14:28.380 --> 14:30.330
Hey, Pops, now you're
putting a lot on it.

14:30.330 --> 14:33.620
Am I? If that's not the case,
what if I said...

14:33.620 --> 14:35.170
Ben Carson?

14:35.170 --> 14:36.790
Ben Carson.

14:36.790 --> 14:38.500
Unh-unh. Nope.

14:38.500 --> 14:40.750
Oh, you talking about
the soul brother

14:40.750 --> 14:44.040
who said slaves were
a bunch of Black immigrants

14:44.040 --> 14:47.080
coming to America
looking for a better life?

14:47.080 --> 14:50.420
The man performed the first
successful brain surgery

14:50.420 --> 14:52.750
on a baby in the womb.

14:52.750 --> 14:54.960
Matter of fact,
I remember you said

14:54.960 --> 14:57.580
the movie about him
was inspirational, Dre.

14:58.920 --> 15:02.290
Cuba Gooding Jr. had me thinking
he was Ben Carson.

15:02.290 --> 15:04.710
Ooh, can we put Cuba
on the list?

15:04.710 --> 15:06.210
Whoa, whoa.

15:06.210 --> 15:08.540
So you're saying "Boat Trip"
is about Ben Carson?

15:08.540 --> 15:11.380
Boy, we are not putting
Ben Carson on the list!

15:11.380 --> 15:13.330
A man's life's work
doesn't disappear

15:13.330 --> 15:15.120
just because you disagree
with his politics.

15:15.120 --> 15:16.580
The point I'm making
is that

15:16.580 --> 15:19.460
you are not the king
of all Black people, Dre.

15:19.460 --> 15:21.120
Mm-hmm.
Yeah, Dad,
just admit it.

15:21.120 --> 15:22.790
You have
some blind spots.

15:22.790 --> 15:24.000
I mean,
we keep on giving you

15:24.000 --> 15:25.830
all of these suggestions
to help,

15:25.830 --> 15:28.540
and you just keep shooting us
down for no good reason.

15:28.540 --> 15:29.750
Oh, I have reasons --
Dre.

15:29.750 --> 15:31.830
You should listen
to the kids' suggestions

15:31.830 --> 15:33.880
before you make
your final decision.

15:33.880 --> 15:36.170
As if you're any better
at listening to us.

15:36.170 --> 15:37.500
What?
Diane.

15:37.500 --> 15:38.500
Forget it.

15:38.500 --> 15:40.540
Just make it
whoever you want.

15:40.540 --> 15:43.000
I'll just sit through
the presentation, like usual.

15:43.000 --> 15:44.580
Jack:
This whole thing stinks.

15:44.580 --> 15:47.040
You're supposed to be doing this
for our school,

15:47.040 --> 15:48.120
but we don't get
any say.

15:48.120 --> 15:50.330
It's not a good look,
Dre.

15:50.330 --> 15:52.420
No, it's okay.
Dre knows best.

15:52.420 --> 15:55.670
When someone asks you
to talk about somebody,

15:55.670 --> 15:57.250
pick whoever you want.

15:57.250 --> 16:00.120
But in a few hours,
I am going to present

16:00.120 --> 16:03.710
an inspirational,
squeaky-clean dead guy

16:03.710 --> 16:07.080
with major accomplishments
and no skeletons in his closet,

16:07.080 --> 16:09.420
so no one can say
he does not belong,

16:09.420 --> 16:11.920
and that person is
Lewis Howard Latimer!

16:11.920 --> 16:12.920
[ Sighs ]

16:12.920 --> 16:14.170
That's it.

16:14.170 --> 16:15.460
Okay. Gosh.
And you know what?

16:15.460 --> 16:18.040
You guys don't deserve
Latimer's lightbulbs.

16:18.040 --> 16:19.500
Wha-- Ah!

16:19.500 --> 16:21.420
[ Scoffs ]

16:21.420 --> 16:22.920
Those are LED!

16:28.080 --> 16:29.080
[ Door closes ]

16:29.080 --> 16:31.790
Brought you back a burger.

16:31.790 --> 16:34.500
Your betrayal killed
my appetite,

16:34.500 --> 16:37.170
so I have to finish
my Latimer presentation.

16:37.170 --> 16:39.080
I was just trying
to help.

16:39.080 --> 16:40.790
I didn't mean
to get you all upset.

16:40.790 --> 16:41.790
I did.

16:41.790 --> 16:43.330
You were being an ass.

16:43.330 --> 16:44.580
Really?

16:44.580 --> 16:46.250
Maybe I was
messing with you --

16:46.250 --> 16:47.920
bring you down
off your high horse --

16:47.920 --> 16:50.000
but I don't like it
when you talk to me

16:50.000 --> 16:51.710
like I'm
a know-nothing old man,

16:51.710 --> 16:54.460
just like you didn't like it
when Junior knew more than you.

16:54.460 --> 16:56.620
Cheating in the bathroom
is beneath you, big guy.

16:56.620 --> 16:59.380
Instead of being mad,
you should be proud

16:59.380 --> 17:01.750
that you raised kids
that know so much

17:01.750 --> 17:04.120
about Black history and culture
in all its forms.

17:04.120 --> 17:05.620
Like you are of me?

17:05.620 --> 17:08.080
I didn't say that.
[ Chuckles ]

17:08.080 --> 17:10.880
I like it when you keep pushing
for the new kids on the block,

17:10.880 --> 17:13.040
but I'm still gonna keep riding
for the classics.

17:13.040 --> 17:14.670
See, I worry that if
they don't teach the classics

17:14.670 --> 17:17.210
during Black History Month,
they'll just fade away.

17:17.210 --> 17:19.500
Too many people
look for excuses

17:19.500 --> 17:21.250
to just forget
the hard parts of our story.

17:21.250 --> 17:22.710
We have to keep
reminding them.

17:22.710 --> 17:24.040
I hear you, Pops.

17:24.040 --> 17:25.500
And I just want to say

17:25.500 --> 17:27.710
that I'm sorry
for being a jerk about Latimer.

17:27.710 --> 17:30.210
You took all of the lightbulbs
out of our bedrooms.

17:33.250 --> 17:36.670
I didn't realize it was gonna be
so much pressure.

17:36.670 --> 17:39.250
You know, I saw this
as my chance to show the kids

17:39.250 --> 17:41.290
a bigger picture
of who we are,

17:41.290 --> 17:43.170
but then I had to compress
all of our history

17:43.170 --> 17:46.920
into just one more person.

17:46.920 --> 17:49.250
A lot is riding
on me getting this right.

17:49.250 --> 17:50.040
Wow.

17:51.670 --> 17:53.040
Now I kind of feel bad

17:53.040 --> 17:54.790
for eating most of your burger
on the way home.

17:54.790 --> 17:56.380
Don't do that, son.

17:56.380 --> 17:59.040
We got to take these moments
to kick him while he's down.

18:02.620 --> 18:04.620
I'll be taking this.

18:04.620 --> 18:10.620
♪♪

18:13.540 --> 18:17.210
Okay, we are so lucky
to have Mr. Johnson here

18:17.210 --> 18:20.830
to tell us about
one more great Black American

18:20.830 --> 18:23.790
before we close the book
on Black History Month

18:23.790 --> 18:25.380
for another year.

18:25.380 --> 18:26.170
Yes.

18:29.330 --> 18:30.880
Thank you, Ms. Davis.

18:30.880 --> 18:34.750
Um, I'm actually going to do,
uh, things a little differently.

18:34.750 --> 18:36.000
We had a deal.

18:36.000 --> 18:37.580
I told you
he would do this.

18:37.580 --> 18:38.710
Okay, hey, guys.

18:38.710 --> 18:41.790
Um...I racked my brain

18:41.790 --> 18:44.540
trying to find the one person
to tell you about today,

18:44.540 --> 18:47.120
and that's how I came up with
Lewis Latimer --

18:47.120 --> 18:51.830
inventor, child of slaves,
proud partner of Thomas Edison.

18:51.830 --> 18:55.080
But the thing is,
there is no one.

18:55.080 --> 18:56.960
There are so many people
to talk about,

18:56.960 --> 19:00.040
and 28 days isn't long enough

19:00.040 --> 19:03.540
to contain
their influence and greatness.

19:03.540 --> 19:07.170
Just like the white heroes that
you learn about all year long,

19:07.170 --> 19:10.210
you should be learning about
these Black heroes, too.

19:10.210 --> 19:11.620
And not just Lewis Latimer.

19:11.620 --> 19:13.710
Joycelyn Elders.

19:13.710 --> 19:15.750
DeRay Mckesson.

19:15.750 --> 19:19.210
And Aretha Franklin
and Harriet Tubman

19:19.210 --> 19:20.330
and LeBron.

19:20.330 --> 19:23.170
[ Scattered hooting ]
Right?

19:23.170 --> 19:26.580
And someone
sitting in this room right now.

19:26.580 --> 19:28.710
You should also know artists

19:28.710 --> 19:32.960
like Kehinde Wiley
and Kara Walker.

19:32.960 --> 19:35.380
Black Lives Matter founders

19:35.380 --> 19:38.830
Alicia Garza, Patrisse Cullors,
and Opal Tometi.

19:38.830 --> 19:40.710
Dr. Ben Carson --

19:40.710 --> 19:42.580
but only for the surgery stuff.

19:42.580 --> 19:45.880
Cannot forget about
my man Lonnie Johnson,

19:45.880 --> 19:48.120
who created the Super Soaker.

19:48.120 --> 19:49.500
[ Laughter ]

19:49.500 --> 19:51.960
Journalist Ida B. Wells.

19:51.960 --> 19:55.790
Or civil rights icon
Bayard Rustin.

19:55.790 --> 20:00.750
Or medical pioneer
Doctor McStuffins.

20:00.750 --> 20:03.040
[ Laughter ]

20:03.040 --> 20:06.750
Dre: Black History Month
may be over on February 28th,

20:06.750 --> 20:09.290
but that doesn't mean
we have to stop celebrating

20:09.290 --> 20:11.750
the fullness
of Black achievement.

20:11.750 --> 20:14.620
We can celebrate it
every day of the year,

20:14.620 --> 20:17.120
and we still won't get to
all the people

20:17.120 --> 20:19.750
who deserve to be included
in the conversation.

20:19.750 --> 20:21.500
But that doesn't mean
I'm going to stop trying.

20:24.960 --> 20:29.210
Andre Johnson -- husband,
father, advertising visionary.

20:29.210 --> 20:32.120
Growing up in Compton,
Johnson knew he would one day

20:32.120 --> 20:34.330
climb to the heights
of the ad game.

20:34.330 --> 20:37.620
Along the way, married
a smoking-hot doctor wife

20:37.620 --> 20:39.170
and had five children,

20:39.170 --> 20:40.710
most of whom he likes.

20:40.710 --> 20:42.540
He's a true American hero

20:42.540 --> 20:46.420
and the owner of the dopest
shoe collection in Sherman Oaks.

20:46.420 --> 20:49.580
And that's a Black person
you should know.

20:49.580 --> 20:51.080
[ Sighs ] Is this the kind
of person we're doing now?

20:51.080 --> 20:52.460
Just a dude with some shoes?

20:52.460 --> 20:53.710
Cut! [ Groans ]

20:53.710 --> 20:55.080
Stupid.

20:55.080 --> 20:57.210
If you could, uh --

20:57.210 --> 20:59.790
If you could just read the
cue cards, that would be great.

20:59.790 --> 21:01.880
You know, we paid a lot
to fly you out here.

21:01.880 --> 21:03.210
It just seems weird.

21:03.210 --> 21:04.790
I mean, of all the people
in the world to pick.

21:04.790 --> 21:06.420
Read the lines, Octavia.

21:06.420 --> 21:08.210
[ Both chuckle ]

21:08.210 --> 21:10.500
You know I have an Oscar,
right?

21:10.500 --> 21:11.960
So does Mo'Nique.

21:11.960 --> 21:13.960
But she was unavailable.

21:13.960 --> 21:15.040
We can roll.

21:15.040 --> 21:16.120
Man: Sound speed!

21:16.120 --> 21:17.420
[ Chuckles ]
Rolling!

21:18.580 --> 21:20.460
Andre Johnson --

21:20.460 --> 21:23.830
husband, father, jackass.

21:23.830 --> 21:25.500
-Mom!
-Shh! Daddy's working!
